{"snp5.1":{"snp5.1:0.1":{"pli":"Sutta Nipāta 5.1 ","eng":"Anthology of Discourses 5.1 ","html":"<article id='snp5.1'><header><ul><li class='division'>{}</li></ul>"},"snp5.1:0.2":{"pli":"Vatthugāthā ","eng":"Introductory Verses ","html":"<h1 class='sutta-title'>{}</h1></header>"},"snp5.1:1.1":{"pli":"Kosalānaṃ purā rammā, ","eng":"From the fair city of the Kosalans ","html":"<blockquote class='gatha'><p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:1.2":{"pli":"agamā dakkhiṇāpathaṃ; ","eng":"to the southern region ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:1.3":{"pli":"Ākiñcaññaṃ patthayāno, ","eng":"came a brahmin expert in hymns, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"<i lang='pi' translate='no'>Ākiñcaññaṁ</i> (“nothingness”) refers to “the dimension of nothingness”, which is an important topic in the chapters to come. It seems he was an acolyte of the Kosalan brahmins such as Āḷāra Kālāma who taught the state of nothingsness as the highest realization, and wanted to find a secluded place to pursue his meditations (<a href='index.html?q=mn26#15.1'>MN 26:15.1</a>). The sense of “owning nothing” is also relevant. "},"snp5.1:1.4":{"pli":"brāhmaṇo mantapāragū. ","eng":"aspiring to nothingness. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:2.1":{"pli":"So assakassa visaye, ","eng":"He settled in a region under the shared dominion ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:2.2":{"pli":"aḷakassa samāsane; ","eng":"of Assaka and Muḷaka, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"The inscription Siri Pulumayi at Nasik supports the spelling <i lang='pi' translate='no'>muḷaka</i>. (Sylvain Lévi, “Gonarda, The Cradle of the Gonardiya”, Journal Of The Andhra Historical Society, vol.9, pt.1, July 1934, pg. 8.) "},"snp5.1:2.3":{"pli":"Vasi godhāvarīkūle, ","eng":"where he lived on the bank of the Godāvarī River, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"This is the only early occurrence of this famed sacred river of the south. It arises near Nashik, Maharashtra, not far from Mumbai on the west coast, and flows east for 1,465 kilometres before emptying in the Bay of Bengal. The name <i lang='pi' translate='no'>godāvarī</i> means “granter of cows” due to the abundance the river brings to the lands through which it flows. The town at its source was called Govardhana, “cow-prosperity”. Normally spelled <i lang='pi' translate='no'>godhāvarī</i> in Pali, the form <i lang='pi' translate='no'>godāvarī</i> is standard in Sanskrit, including Buddhist texts (eg. Mahāvastu 3.363) and it seems the Pali spelling is an error. "},"snp5.1:2.4":{"pli":"uñchena ca phalena ca. ","eng":"getting by on gleanings and fruit. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:3.1":{"pli":"Tasseva upanissāya, ","eng":"He was supported ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:3.2":{"pli":"gāmo ca vipulo ahu; ","eng":"by a prosperous village nearby. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:3.3":{"pli":"Tato jātena āyena, ","eng":"With the revenue earned from there ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:3.4":{"pli":"mahāyaññamakappayi. ","eng":"he performed a great sacrifice. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:4.1":{"pli":"Mahāyaññaṃ yajitvāna, ","eng":"When he had completed the great sacrifice, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:4.2":{"pli":"puna pāvisi assamaṃ; ","eng":"he returned to his hermitage once more. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:4.3":{"pli":"Tasmiṃ paṭipaviṭṭhamhi, ","eng":"Upon his return, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:4.4":{"pli":"añño āgañchi brāhmaṇo. ","eng":"another brahmin arrived. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:5.1":{"pli":"Ugghaṭṭapādo tasito, ","eng":"Foot-sore and thirsty, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:5.2":{"pli":"paṅkadanto rajassiro; ","eng":"with grotty teeth and dusty head, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:5.3":{"pli":"So ca naṃ upasaṅkamma, ","eng":"he approached the other ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:5.4":{"pli":"satāni pañca yācati. ","eng":"and asked for five hundred coins. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:6.1":{"pli":"Tamenaṃ bāvarī disvā, ","eng":"When Bāvari saw him, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:6.2":{"pli":"āsanena nimantayi; ","eng":"he invited him to sit down, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:6.3":{"pli":"Sukhañca kusalaṃ pucchi, ","eng":"asked of his happiness and well-being, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:6.4":{"pli":"idaṃ vacanamabravi. ","eng":"and said the following. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:7.1":{"pli":"“Yaṃ kho mama deyyadhammaṃ, ","eng":"“Whatever I had available to give, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:7.2":{"pli":"Sabbaṃ visajjitaṃ mayā; ","eng":"I have already distributed. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:7.3":{"pli":"Anujānāhi me brahme, ","eng":"Believe me, brahmin, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:7.4":{"pli":"Natthi pañcasatāni me”. ","eng":"I don’t have five hundred coins.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:8.1":{"pli":"“Sace me yācamānassa, ","eng":"“If, good fellow, you do not ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:8.2":{"pli":"bhavaṃ nānupadassati; ","eng":"give me what I ask, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:8.3":{"pli":"Sattame divase tuyhaṃ, ","eng":"then on the seventh day, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:8.4":{"pli":"muddhā phalatu sattadhā”. ","eng":"let your head explode in seven!” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>","comm":"The threat of losing one’s head is found at eg. Chāndogya Upaniṣad 1.8.6 and Bṛhadāraṇyaka Upaniṣad 1.3.24, or at 3.9.26 when it actually did fall off. I cannot trace the detail of heads being split in seven to any early Sanskrit texts, but it is found in later texts such as Rāmāyaṇa 7.26.44c and Mahābhārata 14.7.2c. "},"snp5.1:9.1":{"pli":"Abhisaṅkharitvā kuhako, ","eng":"After performing a ritual, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:9.2":{"pli":"bheravaṃ so akittayi; ","eng":"that charlatan uttered his dreadful curse. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:9.3":{"pli":"Tassa taṃ vacanaṃ sutvā, ","eng":"When he heard these words, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:9.4":{"pli":"bāvarī dukkhito ahu. ","eng":"Bāvari became distressed. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:10.1":{"pli":"Ussussati anāhāro, ","eng":"Not eating, he grew emaciated, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:10.2":{"pli":"Sokasallasamappito; ","eng":"stricken by the dart of sorrow. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:10.3":{"pli":"Athopi evaṃ cittassa, ","eng":"And in such a state of mind, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:10.4":{"pli":"Jhāne na ramatī mano. ","eng":"he could not enjoy absorption. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:11.1":{"pli":"Utrastaṃ dukkhitaṃ disvā, ","eng":"Seeing him anxious and distraught, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:11.2":{"pli":"Devatā atthakāminī; ","eng":"a goddess wishing to help, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:11.3":{"pli":"Bāvariṃ upasaṅkamma, ","eng":"approached Bāvari ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:11.4":{"pli":"Idaṃ vacanamabravi. ","eng":"and said the following. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:12.1":{"pli":"“Na so muddhaṃ pajānāti, ","eng":"“That charlatan understands nothing ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:12.2":{"pli":"Kuhako so dhanatthiko; ","eng":"about the head, he only wants money. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:12.3":{"pli":"Muddhani muddhapāte vā, ","eng":"When it comes to heads or head-splitting, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:12.4":{"pli":"Ñāṇaṃ tassa na vijjati”. ","eng":"he has no knowledge at all.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:13.1":{"pli":"“Bhotī carahi jānāsi, ","eng":"“Then you, Madam, must know—","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:13.2":{"pli":"Taṃ me akkhāhi pucchitā; ","eng":"please answer my question. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:13.3":{"pli":"Muddhaṃ muddhādhipātañca, ","eng":"Let me hear what you say ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:13.4":{"pli":"Taṃ suṇoma vaco tava”. ","eng":"about heads and head-splitting.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:14.1":{"pli":"“Ahampetaṃ na jānāmi, ","eng":"“I too do not know that, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:14.2":{"pli":"Ñāṇamettha na vijjati; ","eng":"I have no knowledge in that matter. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:14.3":{"pli":"Muddhani muddhādhipāte ca, ","eng":"When it comes to heads or head-splitting, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:14.4":{"pli":"Jinānaṃ hettha dassanaṃ”. ","eng":"it is the Victors who have vision.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:15.1":{"pli":"“Atha ko carahi jānāti, ","eng":"“So who then, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:15.2":{"pli":"Asmiṃ pathavimaṇḍale; ","eng":"in all this vast territory, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"Note that, in the EBTs, <i lang='pi' translate='no'>pathavimaṇḍala</i> primarily refers to the region ruled by a Wheel-Turning Monarch. Thus it doesn’t mean “circle” in the sense of “the circle of the earth” but rather a “sphere of influence”, i.e. “territory”. "},"snp5.1:15.3":{"pli":"Muddhaṃ muddhādhipātañca, ","eng":"does know about heads and head-splitting? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:15.4":{"pli":"Taṃ me akkhāhi devate”. ","eng":"Please tell me, goddess.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:16.1":{"pli":"“Purā kapilavatthumhā, ","eng":"“From the city of Kapilavatthu ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"<i lang='pi' translate='no'>Purā</i> can be either “from the city” (Norman), or “formerly” (commentary, followed by Bodhi and Jayawickrama). I think the poet is deliberately echoing the opening line of the text, where it must mean “from the city”. "},"snp5.1:16.2":{"pli":"Nikkhanto lokanāyako; ","eng":"the World Leader has gone forth. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:16.3":{"pli":"Apacco okkākarājassa, ","eng":"He is a scion of King Okkāka, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:16.4":{"pli":"Sakyaputto pabhaṅkaro. ","eng":"a Sakyan, and a beacon. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:17.1":{"pli":"So hi brāhmaṇa sambuddho, ","eng":"For he, brahmin, is the Awakened One! ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:17.2":{"pli":"Sabbadhammāna pāragū; ","eng":"He has gone beyond all things; ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:17.3":{"pli":"Sabbābhiññābalappatto, ","eng":"he has attained to all knowledge and power; ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:17.4":{"pli":"Sabbadhammesu cakkhumā; ","eng":"his eye sees clearly in all things, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"“He is the one of clear eye regarding all things.” "},"snp5.1:17.5":{"pli":"Sabbakammakkhayaṃ patto, ","eng":"he has attained the end of all deeds; ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:17.6":{"pli":"Vimutto upadhikkhaye. ","eng":"he is freed with the ending of attachments. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:18.1":{"pli":"Buddho so bhagavā loke, ","eng":"That Buddha, the Blessed One in the world, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:18.2":{"pli":"Dhammaṃ deseti cakkhumā; ","eng":"the Clear-eyed One, teaches Dhamma. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:18.3":{"pli":"Taṃ tvaṃ gantvāna pucchassu, ","eng":"Go to him and ask—","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:18.4":{"pli":"So te taṃ byākarissati”. ","eng":"he will answer you.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:19.1":{"pli":"Sambuddhoti vaco sutvā, ","eng":"When he heard the word “Buddha”, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:19.2":{"pli":"Udaggo bāvarī ahu; ","eng":"Bāvari was elated. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:19.3":{"pli":"Sokassa tanuko āsi, ","eng":"His sorrow faded, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:19.4":{"pli":"Pītiñca vipulaṃ labhi. ","eng":"and he was filled to brimming with joy. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:20.1":{"pli":"So bāvarī attamano udaggo, ","eng":"Uplifted, elated, and inspired, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:20.2":{"pli":"Taṃ devataṃ pucchati vedajāto; ","eng":"Bāvari questioned that goddess: ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:20.3":{"pli":"“Katamamhi gāme nigamamhi vā pana, ","eng":"“But in what village or town, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:20.4":{"pli":"Katamamhi vā janapade lokanātho; ","eng":"or in what land is the protector of the world, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:20.5":{"pli":"Yattha gantvāna passemu, ","eng":"where we may go and pay respects ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:20.6":{"pli":"Sambuddhaṃ dvipaduttamaṃ”. ","eng":"to the Awakened One, best of men?” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:21.1":{"pli":"“Sāvatthiyaṃ kosalamandire jino, ","eng":"“Near Sāvatthī, home of the Kosalans, <j>is the Victor ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"<i lang='pi' translate='no'>Mandira</i> is unusual and probably a sign of lateness. Bodhi has “realm”, Norman “city”, but the normal meaning in Sanskrit is a “dwelling place”, and in the Jātakas it is always used in the sense of a home. "},"snp5.1:21.2":{"pli":"Pahūtapañño varabhūrimedhaso; ","eng":"abounding in wisdom, vast in intelligence. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:21.3":{"pli":"So sakyaputto vidhuro anāsavo, ","eng":"That Sakyan is indefatigable, free of defilements, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"The commentary gives the senses <i lang='pi' translate='no'>vigatadhuro</i> “free of burden” (followed by Norman) and <i lang='pi' translate='no'>appaṭimo</i> “unrivalled” (followed by Bodhi), but at <a href='index.html?q=an3.20#2.1'>AN 3.20:2.1</a> it has the sense “indefatigable” and there seems no reason why it shouldn’t have the same meaning here. "},"snp5.1:21.4":{"pli":"Muddhādhipātassa vidū narāsabho”. ","eng":"that captain of men understands head-splitting.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:22.1":{"pli":"Tato āmantayī sisse, ","eng":"Therefore he addressed his acolytes, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:22.2":{"pli":"Brāhmaṇe mantapārage; ","eng":"brahmins who had mastered the hymns: ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:22.3":{"pli":"“Etha māṇavā akkhissaṃ, ","eng":"“Come, students, I shall speak. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:22.4":{"pli":"Suṇātha vacanaṃ mama. ","eng":"Listen to what I say. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:23.1":{"pli":"Yasseso dullabho loke, ","eng":"Today has arisen in the world ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:23.2":{"pli":"Pātubhāvo abhiṇhaso; ","eng":"one whose appearance in the world ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:23.3":{"pli":"Svājja lokamhi uppanno, ","eng":"is hard to find again—","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:23.4":{"pli":"Sambuddho iti vissuto; ","eng":"he is renowned as the Awakened One. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:23.5":{"pli":"Khippaṃ gantvāna sāvatthiṃ, ","eng":"Quickly go to Sāvatthī ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:23.6":{"pli":"Passavho dvipaduttamaṃ”. ","eng":"and see the best of men.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:24.1":{"pli":"“Kathaṃ carahi jānemu, ","eng":"“Brahmin, how then are we to know ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:24.2":{"pli":"Disvā buddhoti brāhmaṇa; ","eng":"the Buddha when we see him? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:24.3":{"pli":"Ajānataṃ no pabrūhi, ","eng":"We don’t know, please tell us, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:24.4":{"pli":"Yathā jānemu taṃ mayaṃ”. ","eng":"so we can recognize him.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:25.1":{"pli":"“Āgatāni hi mantesu, ","eng":"“The marks of a great man ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:25.2":{"pli":"Mahāpurisalakkhaṇā; ","eng":"have been handed down in our hymns. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:25.3":{"pli":"Dvattiṃsāni ca byākkhātā, ","eng":"Thirty-two have been described, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:25.4":{"pli":"Samattā anupubbaso. ","eng":"complete and in order. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:26.1":{"pli":"Yassete honti gattesu, ","eng":"One upon whose body is found ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:26.2":{"pli":"Mahāpurisalakkhaṇā; ","eng":"these marks of a great man ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:26.3":{"pli":"Dveyeva tassa gatiyo, ","eng":"has two possible destinies, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:26.4":{"pli":"Tatiyā hi na vijjati. ","eng":"there is no third. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:27.1":{"pli":"Sace agāraṃ āvasati, ","eng":"If he stays at home, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:27.2":{"pli":"Vijeyya pathaviṃ imaṃ; ","eng":"having conquered this land ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:27.3":{"pli":"Adaṇḍena asatthena, ","eng":"without rod or sword, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:27.4":{"pli":"Dhammena manusāsati. ","eng":"he shall govern by principle. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:28.1":{"pli":"Sace ca so pabbajati, ","eng":"But if he goes forth ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:28.2":{"pli":"Agārā anagāriyaṃ; ","eng":"from the lay life to homelessness, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:28.3":{"pli":"Vivaṭṭacchado sambuddho, ","eng":"he becomes an Awakened One, a perfected one, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:28.4":{"pli":"Arahā bhavati anuttaro. ","eng":"with veil cast off, supreme. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:29.1":{"pli":"Jātiṃ gottañca lakkhaṇaṃ, ","eng":"Ask him about my birth, clan, and marks, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:29.2":{"pli":"Mante sisse punāpare; ","eng":"my hymns and acolytes; and further, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:29.3":{"pli":"Muddhaṃ muddhādhipātañca, ","eng":"about heads and head-splitting—","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:29.4":{"pli":"Manasāyeva pucchatha. ","eng":"but do so only in your mind! ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:30.1":{"pli":"Anāvaraṇadassāvī, ","eng":"If he is the Buddha ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:30.2":{"pli":"Yadi buddho bhavissati; ","eng":"of unhindered vision, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:30.3":{"pli":"Manasā pucchite pañhe, ","eng":"he will answer with his voice ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:30.4":{"pli":"Vācāya vissajessati”. ","eng":"the questions in your mind.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:31.1":{"pli":"Bāvarissa vaco sutvā, ","eng":"Sixteen brahmin acolytes ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:31.2":{"pli":"Sissā soḷasa brāhmaṇā; ","eng":"heard what Bāvari said: ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:31.3":{"pli":"Ajito tissametteyyo, ","eng":"Ajita, Tissametteyya, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:31.4":{"pli":"Puṇṇako atha mettagū. ","eng":"Puṇṇaka and Mettagū, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:32.1":{"pli":"Dhotako upasīvo ca, ","eng":"Dhotaka and Upasīva, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:32.2":{"pli":"Nando ca atha hemako; ","eng":"Nanda and then Hemaka, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:32.3":{"pli":"Todeyya-kappā dubhayo, ","eng":"both Todeyya and Kappa, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:32.4":{"pli":"Jatukaṇṇī ca paṇḍito. ","eng":"and Jatukaṇṇī the astute, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:33.1":{"pli":"Bhadrāvudho udayo ca, ","eng":"Bhadrāvudha and Udaya, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:33.2":{"pli":"Posālo cāpi brāhmaṇo; ","eng":"and the brahmin Posāla, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:33.3":{"pli":"Mogharājā ca medhāvī, ","eng":"Mogharāja the intelligent, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:33.4":{"pli":"Piṅgiyo ca mahāisi. ","eng":"and Piṅgiya the great seer. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:34.1":{"pli":"Paccekagaṇino sabbe, ","eng":"Each of them had their own following, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:34.2":{"pli":"Sabbalokassa vissutā; ","eng":"they were renowned the whole world over. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:34.3":{"pli":"Jhāyī jhānaratā dhīrā, ","eng":"Those attentive ones, <j>meditators who love absorption, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"Bodhi omits <i lang='pi' translate='no'>dhīrā</i>. "},"snp5.1:34.4":{"pli":"Pubbavāsanavāsitā. ","eng":"were redolent with the potential <j>of their past deeds. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>","comm":"One of the many signs of lateness in this passage. <i lang='pi' translate='no'>Vāsana</i> in this sense is found only in the very latest strata of canonical and semi-canonical texts such as the Milindapañha, where we find <i lang='pi' translate='no'>pubbe vāsitavāsanā</i> (<a href='index.html?q=mil6.2.1#3.2'>Mil 6.2.1:3.2</a>). "},"snp5.1:35.1":{"pli":"Bāvariṃ abhivādetvā, ","eng":"Having bowed to Bāvari, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:35.2":{"pli":"Katvā ca naṃ padakkhiṇaṃ; ","eng":"and circled him to his right, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:35.3":{"pli":"Jaṭājinadharā sabbe, ","eng":"they set out for the north, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:35.4":{"pli":"Pakkāmuṃ uttarāmukhā. ","eng":"with their dreadlocks and hides. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:36.1":{"pli":"Aḷakassa patiṭṭhānaṃ, ","eng":"First to Patiṭṭhāna of Muḷaka, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"Modern Paithan. "},"snp5.1:36.2":{"pli":"Purimāhissatiṃ tadā; ","eng":"then on to the citadel of Māhissatī; ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"The Sinhalese commentary explains <i lang='pi' translate='no'>puri</i> or <i lang='pi' translate='no'>pura</i> as “former”, while the Burmese commentary explains it as “citadel”. The city continued under this name for many centuries, so “former” seems unlikely. It is modern Maheshwar. "},"snp5.1:36.3":{"pli":"Ujjeniñcāpi gonaddhaṃ, ","eng":"to Ujjenī and Gonaddhā, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"Ujjenī is Ujjain. Gonaddhā is not identified, but must have been near Bhopal. "},"snp5.1:36.4":{"pli":"Vedisaṃ vanasavhayaṃ. ","eng":"and Vedisa, and Vanasa. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>","comm":"Vedisa is modern Vidisha. Vanasa is called Tumbavana in both inscriptions and Pali commentaries, so may be the modern Tumen. "},"snp5.1:37.1":{"pli":"Kosambiñcāpi sāketaṃ, ","eng":"Then to Kosambī and Sāketa, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:37.2":{"pli":"Sāvatthiñca puruttamaṃ; ","eng":"and the supreme city of Sāvatthī; ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:37.3":{"pli":"Setabyaṃ kapilavatthuṃ, ","eng":"on they went to Setavyā and Kapilavatthu, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"Bodhi and Norman have Setavya, but <a href='index.html?q=dn23'>DN 23</a> shows it is feminine. "},"snp5.1:37.4":{"pli":"Kusinārañca mandiraṃ. ","eng":"and the homestead at Kusinārā. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>","comm":"See my remarks on <i lang='pi' translate='no'>mandira</i> above. Kusinārā was famously <em>not</em> a city. "},"snp5.1:38.1":{"pli":"Pāvañca bhoganagaraṃ, ","eng":"To Pāvā they went, and Bhoga City, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:38.2":{"pli":"Vesāliṃ māgadhaṃ puraṃ; ","eng":"and on to Vesālī and the Magadhan city. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:38.3":{"pli":"Pāsāṇakaṃ cetiyañca, ","eng":"Finally they reached the Pāsāṇaka Shrine, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:38.4":{"pli":"Ramaṇīyaṃ manoramaṃ. ","eng":"fair and delightful. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:39.1":{"pli":"Tasitovudakaṃ sītaṃ, ","eng":"Like a thirsty person to cool water, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:39.2":{"pli":"Mahālābhaṃva vāṇijo; ","eng":"like a merchant to great profit, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:39.3":{"pli":"Chāyaṃ ghammābhitattova, ","eng":"like a heat-struck person to shade, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:39.4":{"pli":"Turitā pabbatamāruhuṃ. ","eng":"they quickly climbed the mountain. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:40.1":{"pli":"Bhagavā tamhi samaye, ","eng":"At that time the Buddha ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:40.2":{"pli":"Bhikkhusaṅghapurakkhato; ","eng":"at the fore of the mendicant Saṅgha, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:40.3":{"pli":"Bhikkhūnaṃ dhammaṃ deseti, ","eng":"was teaching the mendicants the Dhamma, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:40.4":{"pli":"Sīhova nadatī vane. ","eng":"like a lion roaring in the jungle. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:41.1":{"pli":"Ajito addasa buddhaṃ, ","eng":"Ajita saw the Buddha, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:41.2":{"pli":"Sataraṃsiṃva bhāṇumaṃ; ","eng":"like the sun shining with a hundred rays, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:41.3":{"pli":"Candaṃ yathā pannarase, ","eng":"like the moon on the fifteenth day ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:41.4":{"pli":"Pāripūriṃ upāgataṃ. ","eng":"when it has come into its fullness. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:42.1":{"pli":"Athassa gatte disvāna, ","eng":"Then he saw his body, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:42.2":{"pli":"Paripūrañca byañjanaṃ; ","eng":"complete in all features. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:42.3":{"pli":"Ekamantaṃ ṭhito haṭṭho, ","eng":"Thrilled, he stood to one side ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:42.4":{"pli":"Manopañhe apucchatha. ","eng":"and asked this question in his mind. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:43.1":{"pli":"“Ādissa jammanaṃ brūhi, ","eng":"“Speak about the brahmin’s birth; ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:43.2":{"pli":"Gottaṃ brūhi salakkhaṇaṃ; ","eng":"of his clan; and his own marks; ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:43.3":{"pli":"Mantesu pāramiṃ brūhi, ","eng":"what hymns is he proficient in; ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:43.4":{"pli":"Kati vāceti brāhmaṇo”. ","eng":"and how many he teaches.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:44.1":{"pli":"“Vīsaṃ vassasataṃ āyu, ","eng":"“His age is a hundred and twenty. ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:44.2":{"pli":"So ca gottena bāvarī; ","eng":"By clan he is a Bāvari. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:44.3":{"pli":"Tīṇissa lakkhaṇā gatte, ","eng":"There are three marks on his body. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:44.4":{"pli":"Tiṇṇaṃ vedāna pāragū. ","eng":"He is a master of the three Vedas, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:45.1":{"pli":"Lakkhaṇe itihāse ca, ","eng":"the teachings on the marks, the testaments, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:45.2":{"pli":"Sanighaṇḍusakeṭubhe; ","eng":"the vocabularies, and the rituals. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:45.3":{"pli":"Pañcasatāni vāceti, ","eng":"He teaches recitation to five hundred, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:45.4":{"pli":"Sadhamme pāramiṃ gato”. ","eng":"and has reached proficiency in his own teaching.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:46.1":{"pli":"“Lakkhaṇānaṃ pavicayaṃ, ","eng":"“O supreme man, cutter of craving, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:46.2":{"pli":"Bāvarissa naruttama; ","eng":"please reveal in detail ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:46.3":{"pli":"Kaṅkhacchida pakāsehi, ","eng":"Bāvari’s marks—","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:46.4":{"pli":"Mā no kaṅkhāyitaṃ ahu”. ","eng":"let us doubt no longer!” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:47.1":{"pli":"“Mukhaṃ jivhāya chādeti, ","eng":"“He can cover his face with his tongue; ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:47.2":{"pli":"Uṇṇassa bhamukantare; ","eng":"there is a tuft of hair between his eyebrows; ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:47.3":{"pli":"Kosohitaṃ vatthaguyhaṃ, ","eng":"his private parts are concealed in a foreskin: ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:47.4":{"pli":"Evaṃ jānāhi māṇava”. ","eng":"know them as this, young man.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:48.1":{"pli":"Pucchañhi kiñci asuṇanto, ","eng":"Hearing the answers ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:48.2":{"pli":"Sutvā pañhe viyākate; ","eng":"without having heard any questions, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:48.3":{"pli":"Vicinteti jano sabbo, ","eng":"all the people, inspired, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:48.4":{"pli":"Vedajāto katañjalī. ","eng":"with joined palms, wondered: ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:49.1":{"pli":"“Ko nu devo vā brahmā vā, ","eng":"“Who is it that asked a question with their mind? ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:49.2":{"pli":"Indo vāpi sujampati; ","eng":"Was it a god or divinity? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:49.3":{"pli":"Manasā pucchite pañhe, ","eng":"Or Indra, Sujā’s husband? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:49.4":{"pli":"Kametaṃ paṭibhāsati”. ","eng":"To whom does the Buddha reply?” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:50.1":{"pli":"“Muddhaṃ muddhādhipātañca, ","eng":"“Bāvari asks ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:50.2":{"pli":"Bāvarī paripucchati; ","eng":"about heads and head-splitting. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:50.3":{"pli":"Taṃ byākarohi bhagavā, ","eng":"May the Buddha please answer, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:50.4":{"pli":"Kaṅkhaṃ vinaya no ise”. ","eng":"and so, O seer, dispel our doubt.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:51.1":{"pli":"“Avijjā muddhāti jānāhi, ","eng":"“Know ignorance as the head, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"This echoes Chāndogya Upaniṣad 1.10 and 1.11, where Uṣasti, an itinerant brahmin wandering east who has just eaten ritually unclean food, warns priests at a royal sacrifice multiple times that one who recites prayers while ignorant (<i lang='pi' translate='no'>avidvān</i>) of their meaning will suffer their head falling off. "},"snp5.1:51.2":{"pli":"Vijjā muddhādhipātinī; ","eng":"and knowledge as the head-splitter, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:51.3":{"pli":"Saddhāsatisamādhīhi, ","eng":"when joined with faith, mindfulness, and immersion, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:51.4":{"pli":"Chandaviriyena saṃyutā”. ","eng":"and enthusiasm and energy.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:52.1":{"pli":"Tato vedena mahatā, ","eng":"At that, the student, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:52.2":{"pli":"Santhambhitvāna māṇavo; ","eng":"full of inspiration, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:52.3":{"pli":"Ekaṃsaṃ ajinaṃ katvā, ","eng":"arranged his antelope-skin cloak over one shoulder, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:52.4":{"pli":"Pādesu sirasā pati. ","eng":"and fell with his head to the Buddha’s feet. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:53.1":{"pli":"“Bāvarī brāhmaṇo bhoto, ","eng":"“Good fellow, the brahmin Bāvari ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:53.2":{"pli":"Saha sissehi mārisa; ","eng":"together with his acolytes, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:53.3":{"pli":"Udaggacitto sumano, ","eng":"elated and happy, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:53.4":{"pli":"Pāde vandati cakkhuma”. ","eng":"bows to your feet, O Clear-eyed One!” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:54.1":{"pli":"“Sukhito bāvarī hotu, ","eng":"“May the brahmin Bāvari be happy, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:54.2":{"pli":"Saha sissehi brāhmaṇo; ","eng":"together with his acolytes. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:54.3":{"pli":"Tvañcāpi sukhito hohi, ","eng":"And may you, too, be happy! ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:54.4":{"pli":"Ciraṃ jīvāhi māṇava. ","eng":"May you live long, young man. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:55.1":{"pli":"Bāvarissa ca tuyhaṃ vā, ","eng":"To Bāvari and you all ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:55.2":{"pli":"Sabbesaṃ sabbasaṃsayaṃ; ","eng":"I grant the opportunity to clear up all doubt. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:55.3":{"pli":"Katāvakāsā pucchavho, ","eng":"Please ask ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:55.4":{"pli":"Yaṃ kiñci manasicchatha”. ","eng":"whatever you want.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.1:56.1":{"pli":"Sambuddhena katokāso, ","eng":"Granted the opportunity by the Buddha, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:56.2":{"pli":"Nisīditvāna pañjalī; ","eng":"they sat down with joined palms. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:56.3":{"pli":"Ajito paṭhamaṃ pañhaṃ, ","eng":"Ajita asked the Realized One ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.1:56.4":{"pli":"Tattha pucchi tathāgataṃ. ","eng":"the first question right there. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p></blockquote>"},"snp5.1:56.5":{"pli":"Vatthugāthā niṭṭhitā. ","eng":"The introductory verses are finished. ","html":"<p class='endsutta'>{}</p></article>"}},"snp5.10":{"snp5.10:0.1":{"pli":"Sutta Nipāta 5.10 ","eng":"Anthology of Discourses 5.10 ","html":"<article id='snp5.10'><header><ul><li class='division'>{}</li></ul>"},"snp5.10:0.2":{"pli":"Todeyyamāṇavapucchā ","eng":"The Questions of Todeyya ","html":"<h1 class='sutta-title'>{}</h1></header>"},"snp5.10:1.1":{"pli":"“Yasmiṃ kāmā na vasanti, ","eng":"“In whom sensual pleasures do not dwell,” ","html":"<blockquote class='gatha'><p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.10:1.2":{"pli":"(iccāyasmā todeyyo) ","eng":"said Venerable Todeyya, ","html":"<span class='speaker'>{}</span>"},"snp5.10:1.3":{"pli":"Taṇhā yassa na vijjati; ","eng":"“and for whom there is no craving, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.10:1.4":{"pli":"Kathaṅkathā ca yo tiṇṇo, ","eng":"and who has crossed over indecision—","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.10:1.5":{"pli":"Vimokkho tassa kīdiso”. ","eng":"of what kind is their liberation?” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.10:2.1":{"pli":"“Yasmiṃ kāmā na vasanti, ","eng":"“In whom sensual pleasures do not dwell,” ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.10:2.2":{"pli":"(todeyyāti bhagavā) ","eng":"replied the Buddha, ","html":"<span class='speaker'>{}</span>"},"snp5.10:2.3":{"pli":"Taṇhā yassa na vijjati; ","eng":"“and for whom there is no craving, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.10:2.4":{"pli":"Kathaṅkathā ca yo tiṇṇo, ","eng":"and who has crossed over indecision—","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.10:2.5":{"pli":"Vimokkho tassa nāparo”. ","eng":"there is no liberation that is further.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.10:3.1":{"pli":"“Nirāsaso so uda āsasāno, ","eng":"“Are they free of hope, <j>or are they still in need of hope? ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.10:3.2":{"pli":"Paññāṇavā so uda paññakappī; ","eng":"Do they possess wisdom, <j>or are they still forming wisdom? ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>","comm":"Bodhi reads <i lang='pi' translate='no'>kappī</i> (against the Niddesa) in the sense “manner”. But it seems unlikely Todeyya, or anyone really, would ask whether a sage merely <em>seemed</em> wise. Surely the question must be whether a sage is someone who is still in the process of learning, a question that has been important to the Buddhist traditions and still is today. "},"snp5.10:3.3":{"pli":"Muniṃ ahaṃ sakka yathā vijaññaṃ, ","eng":"O Sakyan, elucidate the sage to me, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.10:3.4":{"pli":"Taṃ me viyācikkha samantacakkhu”. ","eng":"so that I may understand, All-seer.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.10:4.1":{"pli":"“Nirāsaso so na ca āsasāno, ","eng":"“They are free of hope, <j>they are not in need of hope. ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.10:4.2":{"pli":"Paññāṇavā so na ca paññakappī; ","eng":"They possess wisdom, <j>they are not still forming wisdom. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.10:4.3":{"pli":"Evampi todeyya muniṃ vijāna, ","eng":"That, Todeyya, is how to understand a sage, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.10:4.4":{"pli":"Akiñcanaṃ kāmabhave asattan”ti. ","eng":"one who has nothing, unattached to sensual life.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p></blockquote>"},"snp5.10:4.5":{"pli":"Todeyyamāṇavapucchā navamā. ","html":"<p class='endsutta'>{}</p></article>"}},"snp5.11":{"snp5.11:0.1":{"pli":"Sutta Nipāta 5.11 ","eng":"Anthology of Discourses 5.11 ","html":"<article id='snp5.11'><header><ul><li class='division'>{}</li></ul>"},"snp5.11:0.2":{"pli":"Kappamāṇavapucchā ","eng":"The Questions of Kappa ","html":"<h1 class='sutta-title'>{}</h1></header>"},"snp5.11:1.1":{"pli":"“Majjhe sarasmiṃ tiṭṭhataṃ, ","eng":"“For those overwhelmed by old age and death,” ","html":"<blockquote class='gatha'><p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.11:1.2":{"pli":"(iccāyasmā kappo) ","eng":"said Venerable Kappa, ","html":"<span class='speaker'>{}</span>"},"snp5.11:1.3":{"pli":"Oghe jāte mahabbhaye; ","eng":"“stuck mid-stream ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.11:1.4":{"pli":"Jarāmaccuparetānaṃ, ","eng":"as the terrifying flood arises, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.11:1.5":{"pli":"Dīpaṃ pabrūhi mārisa; ","eng":"tell me an island, good fellow. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.11:1.6":{"pli":"Tvañca me dīpamakkhāhi, ","eng":"Explain to me an island ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.11:1.7":{"pli":"Yathāyidaṃ nāparaṃ siyā”. ","eng":"so this may occur no further.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.11:2.1":{"pli":"“Majjhe sarasmiṃ tiṭṭhataṃ, ","eng":"“For those overwhelmed by old age and death,” ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.11:2.2":{"pli":"(kappāti bhagavā) ","eng":"replied the Buddha, ","html":"<span class='speaker'>{}</span>"},"snp5.11:2.3":{"pli":"Oghe jāte mahabbhaye; ","eng":"“stuck mid-stream ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.11:2.4":{"pli":"Jarāmaccuparetānaṃ, ","eng":"as the terrifying flood arises, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.11:2.5":{"pli":"Dīpaṃ pabrūmi kappa te. ","eng":"I shall tell you an island, Kappa. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.11:3.1":{"pli":"Akiñcanaṃ anādānaṃ, ","eng":"Having nothing, taking nothing: ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.11:3.2":{"pli":"etaṃ dīpaṃ anāparaṃ; ","eng":"this is the island with nothing further. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.11:3.3":{"pli":"Nibbānaṃ iti naṃ brūmi, ","eng":"I call it extinguishment, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.11:3.4":{"pli":"jarāmaccuparikkhayaṃ. ","eng":"the ending of old age and death. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p>"},"snp5.11:4.1":{"pli":"Etadaññāya ye satā, ","eng":"Those who have fully understood this, mindful, ","html":"<p><span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.11:4.2":{"pli":"Diṭṭhadhammābhinibbutā; ","eng":"are quenched in this very life. ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.11:4.3":{"pli":"Na te māravasānugā, ","eng":"They don’t fall under Māra’s sway, ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span>"},"snp5.11:4.4":{"pli":"Na te mārassa paddhagū”ti. ","eng":"nor are they his footmen.” ","html":"<span class='verse-line'>{}</span></p></blockquote>"},"snp5.11:4.5":{"pli":"Kappamāṇavapucchā dasamā. ","html":"<p class='endsutta'>{}</p></article>"}}}